1. Users

Users access the application through web browsers or mobile devices. Their requests are sent to the cloud infrastructure hosted on AWS.

2. Elastic Load Balancer (ELB)

The Elastic Load Balancer receives incoming requests from users and distributes them evenly across multiple EC2 instances. This prevents any single server from becoming overloaded and improves application availability.

3. Amazon EC2 Instances

Amazon EC2 provides virtual machines that host the application. Multiple EC2 instances work together to process user requests efficiently.

4. Auto Scaling Group (ASG)

The Auto Scaling Group automatically increases or decreases the number of EC2 instances based on workload demand. It also replaces unhealthy instances automatically, implementing the self-healing feature.
5. Amazon CloudWatch

CloudWatch continuously monitors system metrics such as CPU utilization, network traffic, and instance health. It generates alarms whenever thresholds are crossed.

6. CloudWatch Alarms

CloudWatch alarms trigger scaling actions whenever CPU utilization becomes too high or too low. These alarms communicate directly with the Auto Scaling Group.

7. Health Checks

Health checks periodically verify whether EC2 instances are functioning correctly. Failed instances are marked unhealthy and replaced automatically.

8. AWS Availability Zones

The infrastructure can be deployed across multiple Availability Zones to improve fault tolerance and ensure application availability even if one data center becomes unavailable.
